    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Actually using `.loc` this does work.\n\n```\nIn [1]: df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(3,3), columns=['a','b', ('foo','bar')])\n\nIn [2]: df\nOut[2]: \n          a         b  (foo, bar)\n0 -1.063028 -1.014174   -0.372167\n1 -1.130360  0.361685    0.052309\n2 -0.490887 -1.622489    0.802482\n\nIn [3]: df[('foo','bar')]\nOut[3]: \n0   -0.372167\n1    0.052309\n2    0.802482\nName: (foo, bar), dtype: float64\n\nIn [5]: df.loc[:,[('foo','bar'),'a']]\nOut[5]: \n   (foo, bar)         a\n0   -0.372167 -1.063028\n1    0.052309 -1.130360\n2    0.802482 -0.490887\n```\n\nThe issue is disambiguation of the indexer (e.g. what you are passing in) is very tricky (and can be done), but is just too complicated.\n"
  },
