    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "I suspected as much, but loc actually don't work if you put the 'a' first ;)\n\n``` python\nIn [7]: df.loc[:,['a',('foo','bar')]]\n...\n/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/numpy/core/numeric.pyc in asarray(a, dtype, order)\n    458 \n    459     \"\"\"\n--> 460     return array(a, dtype, copy=False, order=order)\n    461 \n    462 def asanyarray(a, dtype=None, order=None):\n\nValueError: cannot set an array element with a sequence\n```\n\nMy use case is that I have a dataframe with various statistics. Before presenting, I want to sort a subset  of the columns according to a custom function, where the first value in the tuple is the argument to this sorting key-function. After sorting, I format the tuple values into a string and rename the corresponding columns\n"
